---

<ProjectLayout frontmatter={frontmatter}>
  <!-- The Problem -->
  <div class="problem-section">
    <h2>// The Problem: OneNote Chaos</h2>
    <p class="intro-text">
      I had multiple OneNote notebooks scattered across my digital life: IT notes, class notes,
      personal notes, recipes, project documentation. What started as organization became fragmentation.
    </p>

    <div class="pain-grid">
      {painPoints.map((point) => (
        <div class="pain-card">
          <span class="pain-issue">{point.issue}</span>
          <span class="pain-desc">{point.description}</span>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <p class="frustration-note">
      The final straw was the constant O365 logins and OneDrive sync failures. I needed something
      that was <strong>local-first</strong>, <strong>portable</strong>, and <strong>owned by me</strong>.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- The Solution -->
  <div class="solution-section">
    <h2>// The Solution: Obsidian + Markdown</h2>
    <p>
      Obsidian stores everything as plain markdown files in a local folder. No proprietary formats,
      no cloud lock-in, no login screens. I created a vault folder on Google Drive and use DriveSync
      to access it on mobile devices (free sync that actually works).
    </p>

    <div class="advantage-grid">
      {advantages.map((adv) => (
        <div class="advantage-card">
          <div class="adv-header">
            <span class="adv-icon">{adv.icon}</span>
            <span class="adv-feature">{adv.feature}</span>
          </div>
          <span class="adv-benefit">{adv.benefit}</span>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- PARA Method -->
  <div class="para-section">
    <h2>// Organization: PARA Method</h2>
    <p>
      I adopted the PARA methodology to structure my vault. Combined with an inbox system and
      dedicated organization days, it keeps chaos at bay.
    </p>

    <div class="para-grid">
      {paraStructure.map((item) => (
        <div class="para-card" style={`border-left-color: ${item.color}`}>
          <div class="para-header">
            <span class="para-letter" style={`color: ${item.color}`}>{item.letter}</span>
            <span class="para-name">{item.name}</span>
          </div>
          <span class="para-desc">{item.description}</span>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Workflow -->
  <div class="workflow-section">
    <h2>// Daily Workflow</h2>
    <div class="workflow-steps">
      {workflow.map((step, i) => (
        <div class="workflow-step">
          <div class="step-number">{i + 1}</div>
          <div class="step-content">
            <span class="step-name">{step.step}</span>
            <span class="step-desc">{step.description}</span>
            <span class="step-detail">{step.detail}</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Graph View -->
  <div class="graph-section">
    <h2>// The Knowledge Graph</h2>
    <p>
      The graph view is where the magic happens. Every link between notes creates a visible
      connection, forming a neural network of my knowledge. Concepts I learned years ago surface
      when I'm working on something new.
    </p>
    <div class="graph-container">
      <img src="/graph.png" alt="Obsidian graph view showing interconnected notes" class="graph-image" />
      <p class="graph-caption">
        // My vault's graph view showing interconnected notes across topics
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Features I Love -->
  <div class="features-section">
    <h2>// Features That Changed Everything</h2>

    <div class="feature-block">
      <h3>&gt; Callouts</h3>
      <p>
        Breaking up plain text walls with callout blocks for warnings, tips, examples, and quotes.
        Makes notes scannable and visually engaging.
      </p>
      <div class="callout-demo">
        <div class="demo-callout tip">
          <span class="callout-icon">üí°</span>
          <span class="callout-text">[!tip] Callouts make notes actually readable</span>
        </div>
        <div class="demo-callout warning">
          <span class="callout-icon">‚ö†Ô∏è</span>
          <span class="callout-text">[!warning] Don't skip the organization days</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="feature-block">
      <h3>&gt; Code Blocks</h3>
      <p>
        Triple backticks with syntax highlighting for all my programming notes. Python, Bash,
        PowerShell, SQL: all beautifully formatted and easy to copy.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="feature-block">
      <h3>&gt; MASTER FILES</h3>
      <p>
        Instead of a million sticky notes and Samsung Note files I'd never revisit, I create one
        canonical MASTER FILE per concept and continuously update it. Single source of truth.
        Information I used to have to dig for is now instantly findable.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="feature-block">
      <h3>&gt; Hashtags & Links</h3>
      <p>
        Every note gets tagged and linked to related concepts. The upfront investment pays off
        when the graph view reveals connections I didn't consciously make.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Plugins -->
  <div class="plugins-section">
    <h2>// Plugins</h2>
    <p>
      I started minimal; wanted to master the core workflow before adding complexity. Now my vault
      is robust and I'm ready to explore more powerful plugins.
    </p>

    <div class="plugin-list">
      {plugins.map((plugin) => (
        <div class="plugin-card">
          <div class="plugin-header">
            <span class="plugin-name">{plugin.name}</span>
            <span class="plugin-status">{plugin.status}</span>
          </div>
          <span class="plugin-purpose">{plugin.purpose}</span>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Lessons -->
  <div class="lessons-section">
    <h2>// Lessons Learned</h2>
    <div class="lessons-grid">
      {lessons.map((item) => (
        <div class="lesson-card">
          <span class="lesson-title">{item.lesson}</span>
          <span class="lesson-insight">{item.insight}</span>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Challenges -->
  <div class="challenges-section">
    <h2>// Honest Challenges</h2>
    <ul class="challenge-list">
      <li>
        <strong>Organization Debt:</strong> Putting off sorting the inbox creates a backlog that's
        daunting to tackle. Dedicated organization days are non-negotiable.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Rich Text Export:</strong> Pasting markdown into Word or email adds extra characters.
        But as markdown becomes more universal (and AI tools embrace it), this matters less.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Learning Curve:</strong> The simplified UI felt sparse at first. Took time to
        internalize keyboard shortcuts and markdown syntax. Worth every minute invested.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- What's Next -->
  <div class="next-section">
    <h2>// What's Next</h2>
    <p>
      Now that my vault is robust and my workflow is solid, I'm looking to:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>Explore more plugins for automation and visualization</li>
      <li>Refine my template library</li>
      <li>Build better dashboards with Dataview queries</li>
      <li>Streamline the mobile capture experience</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="closing-note">
      The way markdown works with LLMs, skills, agents, and structured prompting has been an
      unexpected bonus. Learning this syntax hasn't just organized my notes; it's become a
      fundamental skill for working with AI.
    </p>
  </div>
</ProjectLayout>

